div.p:
Good man, if a bodhisattva-mahāsattva can engage in this contemplation, this is named dhyānapāramitā [Perfection of Meditation] and prajñāpāramitā [Perfection of Wisdom]. Why is this? Only by entering into concentration, can he engage in this form of contemplation; the scattered mind cannot.
Dhyānapāramitā is simply Concentration;
prajñā[jñā]pāramitā is simply Contemplation. In such a way, then, he can contemplate True Reality and see with perfect clarity the Attribute of all Dharmas. What is it that is named Seeing the Attribute of all Dharmas? The Attribute of all Dharmas is named the Attribute Devoid of Attributes. The words Devoid of Attributes precisely mean Unconditioned. Precisely this Unconditioned is named Devoid of Attributes. As the bodhisattva can forever cut off such a Devoidness of Attributes, this precisely is the Attribute Devoid of Attributes. Furthermore, Devoid of Attributes is named the Attribute Devoid of Birth. The Attribute Devoid of Attributes is named the Attribute Devoid of Extinction. Devoidness of Birth and Devoidness of Extinction are named the Attribute Devoid of Attributes. As the bodhisattva sees [that dharmas are] without birth, without extinction, without abiding, without unity, without duality, without hatred, without contention, without existence, just as they are, unmoving and unchanging, the bodhisattva knows the nature of the Dharma. This is named True Nature; this is named Nature of the Dharma; this is named Real Nature.

